register(dESCRIPTIONs);
define
    treeExample="An example of two trees. A tree is defined by the tree attribute that sets its source. A tree must have one member that defines a branch that serves as template for its branches. The branch template must hava a leaf attribute that marks the branch as expandable. Some component of the branch template must have an expandTree attribute which provides the method to expand or contract the branch. Each branch should have an indent with an initial width as its first member and may have an expander member that works as described in the description of the left tree below. If there is an expander, it should have the expandTree attribute. Finally, a branch must have a member named entry to display the contents of the branch.";
    leftTree="Note the expander block in the left tree. It gets its value set whenever its branch is created, expanded or contracted. Two entries in the templates registry, expandable and expanded, contain the values that get displayed in the expander. In this example, the values are + and - but they could just as easily be icons or images.";
    rightTree="The right tree does not have an expander and there is no indication that a branch is expandable. Collapsibility is obvious from indentation, however, you only find out if a branch is expandable by clicking on it. Because the expandTree action associated with the entry rather than an expander, you cannot specify another action on the entry (only the first action specified will be found)";
    ;
register(forest);
define
    glen
        hard
            oaks
                pin;
                "broad leaf";
            maples
                sugar;
                rock;
                swamp;
        soft
            pine;
            fir;
            hemlock;
        shrubs
            holly;
            blueberry;
    ;
